A short walktrough the data

The S&P mining data contains information on 40702 mines globally. It contains information on location of these mines, the type of mineral that is explored, and the type of technology used for mining and processing. However, not all mines have complete information on all variables.



Commodities

This is the list of commodities that are explored in the dataset. ‘n’ is the number of mines that explore each commodity, and ‘perc’ is the percentage of mines that explore each commodity. It is possible to see here that around 35 and 13% of the mines explore gold and copper, respectively.




However, some mines have more than one commodity. The table below shows the relationship between the ‘primary commodity’ and the other commodities explored in the same mine. The table is sorted by the number of mines that explore each combination of commodities.

A focus on energy transition minerals

This part of the analysis of the dataset focuses on minerals that are important for the energy transition.

These minerals are: Lithium, Cobalt, Nickel, Graphite, Rare Earth Elements, Copper, and Manganese.

First, we filter the dataset to include mines that explore these minerals more broadly, and then filter to show the mines in which these minerals are the primary commodity.



There are 40702 mines in the dataset. Of these, 13075 explore at least one of the energy transition minerals, and 8330 have one of these minerals as the primary commodity.

The table below show how many mines explore these minerals as their primary commodity.

Simplifying things

Here we applied a new classification to the status of the mines, based on the ACTV_STATUS and DEV_STAGE columns. This is done to simplify our analysis, and to make it easier to visualize the data. The new classification is as follows:

  • Early Exploration: Mines that are in the early stages of exploration, including those that are not yet active.
  • Advanced Exploration: Mines that are in the advanced stages of exploration, but not yet in production.
  • Study & Evaluation: Mines that are being studied or evaluated for potential production.
  • Development: Mines that are in the development stage, preparing for production.
  • Production: Mines that are actively producing minerals.
  • Closure: Mines that are in the process of closing down.
  • Rehabilitation: Mines that are being rehabilitated after closure.
  • Unknown/Other: Mines that do not fit into any of the above categories, or for which the status is unknown.

Further data availability

There is a series of columns in the dataset that could be very helpful for more detailed analysis. However, that data is not available for most of the mines.

Below is a table that shows the percentage of non-missing values for each of these columns, for the mines that are classified as ‘Production’ in the new classification.

The columns are: - MINE_TYPE1: Type of mine - PROJ_START_UP_YR: Year of project start-up - START_UP_YR: Year of mine start-up - MILL_CAPACITY_TONNES_PER_YEAR: Mill capacity in tonnes per year - MINING_METHODS: Mining methods used - PROCESSING_METHODS: Processing methods used
